-- Stock funds worldwide attract $11 bln, most in five weeks - BofA
-- By Sam Forgione
-- Fri May 16, 2014 09:24AM EDT
-- None



NEW YORK, May 16 (Reuters) - Fund investors worldwide poured $11 billion into stock funds in the week ended May 14, marking the biggest inflows into the funds in five weeks, data from a Bank of America Merrill Lynch Global Research report showed on Friday.

U.S.-focused stock funds attracted $6 billion of the net inflows. All of the inflows into U.S.-focused stock funds went toward exchange-traded funds, according to the report, which also cited data from fund-tracker EPFR Global Funds that specialize in emerging markets stocks attracted $500 million in inflows, reversing $700 million in outflows over the prior week. Japanese stock funds also attracted $500 million, marking their biggest inflows in four weeks.